> colors are switched.
> Red is the ground, and the hot wire is black.... 
> Like
> someone else said,
> valuable lesson here, always question the PO's work!
> 
> I didn't....
> 
> > Don't hook it up the other way unless you want to
> FRY everything.  If
> > you have any radio's or other devices, those are
> prone to FRY too!!  My
> > friend fried his amp by hooking it up backwards..
> that was a costly
> > mistake.
> 
> Well, I already did it, that's why I posted in the
> first place.  Not
> sure what is fried and what isn't, just that my red
> light is on.
>   
> > I'd first hook your battery up the correct way. 
> Hook up the wiring
> > harness with all the red cables on it (and a big
> fat
> (probably black)
> > one that goes to the starter) to the positive(+)
> terminal and the other
> > braided one that goes to the chassis to negative
> (-).
> 
> Everything was hooked up properly before I posted, I
> was just wondering
> if anyone had any ideas on why the red light was on.
>  
> > put in the new one, and test out the voltage at
> different points in the
> > car.  Fuse box is probably a good place.  You
> should
> have 12v on your
> > meter.  This is with the key off.
> 
> This is helpful, will do.  Thanks!
> 
> > Then try and see if the car will start.  If it
> does,
> go and test the
> > voltage again and it should be running at around
> 13.7 volts.  If it is,
> > your voltage regulator is still working correctly.
> 
> If it's higher, then
> > it's not working.  I don't know the reprocussions
> of
> having a bad
> > regulator so be careful..
> 
> The car starts fine, it just runs w/ the red light
> on.
> 
> > I don't how else you'd check your regulator, but
> I'm
> sure if I missed
> > something that someone else will chime in.
> 
> One listee replied in pmail w/ a way to repolarize
> the
> generator, which
> I'll try if the voltage doesn't check out.  He
> suggested this:
> 
> "Polarizing the generator is easy. I believe you
> jump
> the D+ to the DF on the
> regulator momentarily only. Check with someone else
> before you do it."
> 
> Can anyone verify this?
> 
